# Yu-Gi-Oh Tournament Companion

A local tournament companion for **Konami Tournament Software (KTS)**.

The app does not replace KTS. Organizers keep using KTS, then import or auto-sync the KTS `.Tournament` file so players can view pairings, standings, and public tournament information from a hosted public page.

---

# Current Features

- Tauri desktop app
- React + Vite frontend
- FastAPI backend auto-started by Tauri in desktop dev mode
- SQLite database
- AppData storage in desktop mode
- KTS `.Tournament` import
- KTS auto-sync watcher
- Current round pairings
- Standings
- Match result management
- QR sharing
- Local public tournament page for development
- Public snapshot/export endpoint
- Hosted publish/unpublish through Cloudflare Worker
- Cloudflare Pages public tournament site
- Automatic hosted snapshot refresh after KTS auto-sync for published tournaments
- Community player history

---

# Tech Stack

Frontend:

- React
- Vite
- Tailwind CSS
- JavaScript
- Tauri v2
- Cloudflare Pages public build target

Backend:

- FastAPI
- SQLAlchemy
- Pydantic
- SQLite

Database:

- Desktop mode: SQLite in the app data directory
- Manual web dev mode: SQLite at `backend/data/app.db`

Hosted public services:

- Cloudflare Worker public snapshot API
- Workers KV for latest public snapshot by `public_id`
- Cloudflare Pages public site at `/tournaments/:publicId`

`DATABASE_URL` is still supported for explicit local configuration, but SQLite is the documented and supported development path.

---

# Supported Development Workflows

## A. Tauri Desktop Dev

This is the main development workflow.

Requirements:

- Python 3.11+
- Node.js
- Rust via rustup
- Microsoft Visual Studio Build Tools with MSVC and Windows SDK components
- WebView2, which is installed on most current Windows systems

Install dependencies:

```bash
cd backend
python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

```bash
cd ../frontend
npm install
```

Run the desktop app:

```bash
cd frontend
npm run tauri:dev
```

In Tauri dev mode:

- Vite starts normally.
- The Tauri shell starts the FastAPI backend automatically from the repository `backend` directory.
- If `127.0.0.1:8000` is already in use, Tauri assumes the backend is already running.
- When the Tauri app exits, it stops the backend process it started.

Desktop mode passes app-data environment variables to FastAPI:

```text
APP_DATA_DIR=%LOCALAPPDATA%\YuGiOhTournamentManager
DATABASE_URL=sqlite:///%LOCALAPPDATA%/YuGiOhTournamentManager/app.db
```

The backend creates the app-data directory automatically, including:

```text
app.db
logs/
settings.json
publishing.env.example
```

For installed release builds, hosted publishing is configured in the app:

```text
Admin dashboard -> Publishing Settings
```

The Publishing API URL and Public Page URL are prefilled with the shipped Cloudflare defaults. The organizer enters the publish key once, and the app stores it locally in:

```text
%LOCALAPPDATA%\YuGiOhTournamentManager\settings.json
```

The publish key is used only by the local backend and is not returned to the frontend after saving. Dev mode continues to support `backend/.env`. `%LOCALAPPDATA%\YuGiOhTournamentManager\publishing.env` remains a backend environment fallback for debugging, but it is no longer required for normal release use.

---

## B. Web Dev / Debug Mode

This mode keeps the browser workflow available for fast frontend/backend debugging.

No external database service is required.

Create `backend/.env` from `backend/.env.example` if needed:

```text
DATABASE_URL=sqlite:///./data/app.db
PUBLIC_SERVICE_URL=https://your-worker.workers.dev
PUBLIC_SITE_URL=https://your-public-site.pages.dev
PUBLIC_PUBLISH_KEY=your-local-secret
```

Start the backend manually:

```bash
cd backend
.venv\Scripts\activate
uvicorn app.main:app --reload
```

Backend:

```text
http://127.0.0.1:8000
```

Swagger docs:

```text
http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs
```

Start the frontend manually:

```bash
cd frontend
npm run dev
```

Frontend:

```text
http://127.0.0.1:5173
```

Manual web dev mode stores data in:

```text
backend/data/app.db
```

---

## C. Hosted Public Site Dev

The hosted public site is a separate Vite target. It does not register admin routes.

Create `frontend/.env.public` from `frontend/.env.public.example`:

```text
VITE_APP_TARGET=public
VITE_PUBLIC_SERVICE_URL=https://your-worker.workers.dev
```

Run the public site locally:

```bash
cd frontend
npm run dev:public
```

Open:

```text
http://127.0.0.1:5173/tournaments/{public_id}
```

Build the public site:

```bash
npm run build:public
```

Cloudflare Pages settings:

```text
Root directory: frontend
Build command: npm run build:public
Build output directory: dist
Environment:
  VITE_APP_TARGET=public
  VITE_PUBLIC_SERVICE_URL=https://your-worker.workers.dev
```

The public target exposes only:

```text
/
/tournaments/:publicId
```

---

## D. Cloudflare Worker Public API

The Worker lives in `public-service/`.

Local development:

```bash
cd public-service
npm install
npm run dev
```

Deploy:

```bash
npm run deploy
```

Required Worker configuration:

```text
PUBLISH_KEY
TOURNAMENT_SNAPSHOTS KV binding
```

Optional:

```text
SNAPSHOT_TTL_HOURS=24
```

Worker endpoints:

```text
GET  /api/health
PUT  /api/tournaments/:publicId
GET  /api/tournaments/:publicId
POST /api/tournaments/:publicId/unpublish
```

Published snapshots expire per tournament after 24 hours without updates by default. Publishing the same tournament again refreshes the snapshot.

---

# KTS Workflow

Recommended live-event workflow:

- Open the tournament in KTS.
- In the desktop app, choose the KTS `.Tournament` file.
- Import once or enable auto-sync.
- Publish the tournament.
- Share the hosted public page link or QR code with players.
- Keep KTS open and save changes as normal. Auto-sync updates local data and refreshes the hosted snapshot for published tournaments.

Advanced fallback imports remain available:

- Round pairings CSV
- Standings CSV

Pairings CSV columns:

- `Table`
- `Player 1`
- `Player 2`

Extra KTS export columns are ignored. BYEs are handled automatically and are not added as players.

---

# Public Snapshot And Publishing

The backend exposes a public-safe tournament snapshot:

```text
GET /tournaments/{tournament_id}/public-snapshot
```

The snapshot is uploaded to the hosted Worker when a tournament is published and after successful KTS auto-sync for already-published tournaments. It excludes private/internal data such as COSSY IDs, local file paths, backend technical state, and internal player/match IDs.

Publish state is available through:

```text
GET  /tournaments/{tournament_id}/publish-status
POST /tournaments/{tournament_id}/publish
POST /tournaments/{tournament_id}/unpublish
```

`PUBLIC_SERVICE_URL` is the Worker API base URL. `PUBLIC_SITE_URL` is the player-facing public site base URL. The desktop frontend displays and shares `PUBLIC_SITE_URL/tournaments/{public_id}` only.

---

# Architecture Philosophy

This project intentionally stays local-first and simple:

- KTS remains the source tournament tool.
- The app provides a better organizer and player display layer.
- SQLite is the default database.
- Tauri desktop mode stores user data outside the repository.
- Manual browser dev mode remains available for debugging.

Primary flow:

```text
KTS
-> Save .Tournament file
-> Import once or auto-sync into app
-> Publish public snapshot to Worker
-> Cloudflare Pages public site reads latest snapshot
```

